<h2>Key Concepts – Chapter 3</h2>

<p><strong>General form of linear equation:</strong> ax + by + c = 0</p>

<p><strong>Types of solutions:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Consistent:</strong> Equations have a unique solution → lines intersect at one point</li>
  <li><strong>Inconsistent:</strong> Equations have no solution → lines are parallel</li>
  <li><strong>Infinitely many solutions:</strong> Lines are coincident (same line)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Conditions for pair of equations a₁x + b₁y + c₁ = 0 and a₂x + b₂y + c₂ = 0:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Unique solution: a₁/a₂ ≠ b₁/b₂</li>
  <li>No solution: a₁/a₂ = b₁/b₂ ≠ c₁/c₂</li>
  <li>Infinite solutions: a₁/a₂ = b₁/b₂ = c₁/c₂</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>Methods of Solving</h2>

<p><strong>1. Graphical Method:</strong> Draw both equations on graph. Point of intersection is the solution.</p>
<p><strong>2. Substitution Method:</strong> Express one variable in terms of other. Substitute in second equation.</p>
<p><strong>3. Elimination Method:</strong> Multiply equations to make coefficients equal. Add or subtract to eliminate one variable.</p>

